[{"name":"Pennington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire and Cumbria):","habitational name from Pennington in Furness (Lancashire), which derives from Old English <i>pening</i> ‘penny’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, or from Pennington in Leigh (Lancashire), which probably derives from the Old English personal name <i>Pinna</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i> (genitive <i>-inga-</i>) + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","habitational name from Pennington (Hampshire), or from Penton Grafton or Penton Mewsey (both Hampshire); see   Penton  . All have the same etymology as Pennington in Furness; see 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Penington","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Pennington  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland.","History: Edward Penington, born in 1667 in Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England, was appointed surveyor-general of the province of PA in 1698 and accompanied William Penn to Philadelphia."]},{"name":"Penton","meanings":["English (mainly Hampshire):","habitational name from Penton Grafton or Penton Mewsey (both Hanmpshire), or from a shortened form of   Pennington   2. The placenames denoted a farm or estate for which a penny tax was payable (Old English <i>pening</i> ‘penny’ + <i>tūn</i>).","in north-west England, a shortened form of   Pennington   1, from either of the places called Pennington in Lancashire."]}]},{"name":"Alan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Alan Pennington was born about 1160, in Farnley, Yorkshire, England as the son of Sir Benedict Pennington and Agnes Lindsay. He had at least 1 son with Agnes de Longville. He died in 1208, in Cheshire, England, at the age of 49."},"et":{"about 1160–1208":"umbes 1160–1208","1160–1208":"1160–1208","–1165":"–1165","1174–1254":"1174–1254","1200–1248":"1200–1248","1130–1185":"1130–1185","–Female":"Surnud","1248":"1248","about 1160":"umbes 1160","1200":"1200","1254":"1254","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","1174":"1174","1160":"1160","1208":"1208","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Mulcastre, Farnley, Yorkshire, England":"Farnley, Yorkshire, England","Muncaster, Copeland Borough, Cumbria, England":"Muncaster, Cumberland, England","Muncaster, Cumbria, England":"Muncaster, Cumberland, England"},"fi":{"about 1160–1208":"noin 1160–1208","1160–1208":"1160–1208","–1165":"–1165","1174–1254":"1174–1254","1200–1248":"1200–1248","1130–1185":"1130–1185","–Female":"Kuollut","1248":"1248","about 1160":"noin 1160","1200":"1200","1254":"1254","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","1174":"1174","1160":"1160","1208":"1208","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Mulcastre, Farnley, Yorkshire, England":"Farnley, Yorkshire, England","Muncaster, Copeland Borough, Cumbria, England":"Muncaster, Cumberland, England","Muncaster, Cumbria, England":"Muncaster, Cumberland, England"},"fr":{"about 1160–1208":"environ 1160–1208","1160–1208":"1160–1208","–1165":"–1165","1174–1254":"1174–1254","1200–1248":"1200–1248","1130–1185":"1130–1185","–Female":"Décédée","1248":"1248","about 1160":"environ 1160","1200":"1200","1254":"1254","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","1174":"1174","1160":"1160","1208":"1208","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Angleterre","Mulcastre, Farnley, 